messages.content: 14.5: Cage of Obligations

((**14.5**))

Voreverl is in the void.
Voreverl takes a moment to take in her lack of surroundings "Oh... Here again. Better than a sinking ship, I guess." She takes a seat and just waits.
The guy with the sunglasses from last time runs over from just outside her vision. "YOU! The one from before...! I knew it couldn't have been a fluke..." ((Image attached so you remember.))

"Oh, hey, you stuck here too? Listen, I'm not really in the mood for a big evil speech. Just, uh... be intimidated by my invasion of your... home, I guess? For being such prominent villains, lawyers sure have no sense of interior design."
He looks confused. "Lawyers? ...Ah, do you have some impression of who I am?"
"What, you wearing that gaudy suit for pleasure?"
He looks at his outfit. "Well, I think formal attire is important in the right contexts."
"Right..." She cracks her knuckles, and stands up "Okay, let's just get this over with. Are you a minion, or a hero? Or just plain unimportant?"

"Hm. Well, I feel like I'd try to do the right thing most of the time. But so would everyone. That doesn't seem like a hero. I guess minion feels apt, in some abstract sense. Under the mechanisms of corporate hierarchy, perhaps all are minions. I don't know if I'm important. Do we know each other?"

"...I want to say no, but I can't say for sure I wouldn't just forget someone as boring as you." She begins to walk in circles around him "Seriously, corporate hierarchy? You're still beholden to that crap? Have some fun, break some rules, let people know your name! Actually, no, don't do that. They need to keep room to remember my name. Which is Voreverl Leocot, by the way."
"I see. Hello, Voreverl. I'm pretty sure I was something with a J... Joe? Maybe."
"That's great, minion number 4... Or, well, I guess number 3 now..." She stops pacing "You didn't, uh, happen to see my... strategy meeting with Eric last time we met, did you?"
"I don't know who that is, so no. I had just awoken here when I spotted someone nearby and walked towards you. That must've been.... I don't really know how long ago. I don't seem to have a watch."

"From the perspective of Voreverl Leocot, it's been a few days. I guess whatever assholes set up this place could have made time all weird and messed up, though. Lost four months of my life from this dimension hopping bullshit."
"I see. The Antarctica Project... I think."
She glares at him "What, you involved in it? You know something, shades? You keeping some tactical advantage from me?"
"I know nothing. I guess that must sound ridiculous - 'what? how couldn't he know anything?'. But it's pretty close to true. I guess I have some woefully cliche memory loss."

"Convenient... for me, that is. Don't have to listen to your life story or whatever. Yes, you'll make a fine minion. A blank slate, no attachments to hold you back from throwing yourself into the heat of battle to protect your dark overlord. Not that I need any more, I'm in no short supply of loyal slaves."
"Haha, what?"
"Look, just swear loyalty to me. I can probably get you out of here if you do."
"I'm not sure what you're asking me to do."

"Look, just..." She sighs "Fine, fine. I'm clearly not getting my point across like this." She takes a breath and puffs out her chest "Gweheheheh! Behold, the unsealed box of Pandora herself! The ten plagues of biblical proportion personified into human form! An evil unlike anything your pea-sized brain could possibly imagine! Bow before Voreverl Leocot, or die a miserable wretch who foolishly stood against the unstoppable march of her evil empire!"
"I see.... Chūnibyō (中二病) (**Eighth-grader syndrome**). Okay. I wouldn't want to get in your way, certainly." He bows respectfully.

"I could do without the armchair psychology, but you have the right idea." She takes out her PDA and thrusts it towards him "Haven't had much luck with this feature so far, to say the least, but no villain ever conquered out of fear. Uh, their own fear, that is. Whatever, point is, you won't be of use to me stuck here. Hold this."
He holds it. "Hm. The design seems vaguely familiar... I would assume this was created by the same people I worked with."
She furrows her brow "...So you are with them."
“Maybe? You say ‘them’ rather disparagingly.”

"The ones behind this joke of a project are my greatest enemy. Well, second behind Bernard Zie. Maybe third behind, uh, that blond chick... Whoever she was. I guess she was more just a representation of the universe ruining my life, though." She crosses her arms in thought "The order doesn't really matter. What does matter is whether or not I can use you as bait."

“Bernard Zie… that’s…”

A monitor with a keyboard attached is now visible. The entire space is kind of vaguely defined, really, but ‘Joe’ appears to have developed an intuition about it, and walks up to the monitor.

“Yes, of course… I had largely dismissed it, but that’s the same name. A record related to Bernard Zie is stored here, for some reason.”

"So, his filth found its way even in here. I'd normally not bother myself with records of a fool's utter failures. Well, maybe for a quick laugh. But gathering information on enemies is the greatest way to ensnare them in a devilishly clever trap by yours truly." She tries to see the monitor over Joe's shoulder "Anything I can use against him? Easy target relatives? Fears? A love of cheese that I can exploit with a human sized mouse trap?"
“*Otokonoko (男の娘)…*” He mutters, scrolling through #deleted-channel. “I don’t really know. He seems quite resilient in his own way. What exactly do you have against him? Is it because he’s gay?”

"...No. What? No. Homosexuality is one of the greatest crimes you can commit in modern society. Were anyone else to do it, I'd hold a deep respect for them. He's just making a mockery of it. That bastard stole my life. Both my original body in Arctica, and my superior body on Earth. He... he tried to erase the existence of Voreverl Leocot! That cannot stand!"

“Your body…? Hm. I guess such a thing… would be possible. It’s all data, abstracted enough…” he murmurs to himself, somehow closing the text stream and opening up what looks to be Microsoft Excel. You have no fucking idea what he’s doing in Microsoft Excel. 

“…Just… just checking. For the sake of posterity. What year is it, to your knowledge?”
"2022, last time I checked. Well, 917 in Arctica. Gweheh, those fools are so behind us, I almost feel bad for them. 'Almost' being the key word, of course."

“I see. Well, I don’t really know what date system is used in Arctica. Or that there was one. 917 sounds exceptionally silly and devoid of meaning to me. But the other is as I fear. I’ll trust you, given I have no other choice. The mention of year in that document made me certain… it should be 1997.”

"You've been stuck here for 25 years...? Well, your life isn't as important as mine, so my loss of four months is still the greater tragic backstory. Regardless, I suppose it's nice to have some company in the department of lives ruined by this project. What do you say, wanna help me tear it down? Get your revenge?"
“I don’t feel confident in such a bold motive, but I’m certainly willing to assist you. Haven’t been granted much else to do.” He holds out your PDA. “Do you want this back?”

She stares at it for a few seconds before snatching it back "I was hoping that'd do something. Lost my last transferable minion, and with you stuck here, you won't exactly be of much use to me... Or, at least, I thought not. That computer do anything other than talk about Bernard Zie and tell you the year?"

“It— well, it has a lot of data visualization software. Really impressive stuff. I believe there should be more information accessible along the lines of that Bernard record, but the navigation is incredibly unintuitive. It also isn’t exactly very promising as a source of information. It reads like an amateur creative writing project.”

"Fools wasting their lives away writing, instead of making their dreams into a reality... That's what separates me from the riffraff. So, these records are all just fiction, then? Someone just couldn't get enough of a real Bernard Zie, they had to make a fake one too?"

“They’re presented as if they’re real, at least. An embellished retelling. I don’t exactly have the means to verify if this really happened. Or ‘really happened’ in the sense that this would be able to.”
"Anything about... *me* in there?"
“No mention of a ‘Voreverl’, no. I’d remember that name.”
"...Hardly a record worth keeping, then. Whatever, useless garbage, how unexpected." She looks around "Anything else in this place? Got a TV and couch to pass the time?"
“Not… that I’m aware of. Though there’s still a lot I don’t know. I witnessed something very peculiar the other… well, I’m inclined to say ‘day’, but I don’t know.”

"Peculiar, huh? Alright then, lay it on me, minion. Got nothing else to do until I get randomly zapped back to... I want to say Earth, but honestly who knows. My existence is a force of chaos, probably threw a wrench into the mastermind's plans just by being here."

“It’s hard to describe, but… I saw a structure of some sort far away. I tried to investigate, but couldn’t seem to get any closer. I could see inside it, too. It’s like… in computer graphics, textures are one-sided by default. So you can look through any wall you stand behind if you exit a building perhaps you were meant to stay inside.” He thinks about trying to explain that again, but doesn’t. “There might have been something in there. Alive.”

"Wow, a structure with see-through walls, this place is getting more exciting by the second. Congratulations developers of The Antarctica Project, you invented glass." She rolls her eyes "Whatever, it sounds like a more interesting evil lair than quite literally nothing. Take me there."

“It’s not here anymore. At least, I can’t see it. I could attempt to recreate it, though.” With unusual familiarity with keyboard shortcuts, and without waiting for confirmation, he opens and utilizes an application for sketching floor-plans. The rough outline he ends up creating is a perfect dodecagon, with 6 doors positioned equally blah blah blah you get the gist. That fucking layout.

"Hm... Not the worst evil lair I've seen. What, does each door lead to a gauntlet for the heroes to overcome and unlock passage to the villain's throne room? Oh, and they could get picked off one by one until it's just the chosen hero... Yeah, that'd be good, real good." She nods to herself.
“It intrigues me that they chose twelve sides. I very particularly remember that.”

"Really? That's what intrigues you? Holy shit, if they let you loose, you could get a higher kill count than me from just boring victims to death. Is this what you do to pass the time? Just count walls?"

“I think there really are twelve walls. It, as an attribute, wins by default in intrigue against your scenario, which did not happen.”
He scratches his head. “Well, maybe it did. I wasn’t close enough to discern what was going on there.”

"You're probably right, no one would be genius enough to think of such a dastardly use of an evil lair before I did. That's what makes me the greatest villain of all time. Unlike you, the greatest wall-counter of all time. Congratulations on your title, you earned it."
“I would assume that title would require a quantity much higher than twelve, actually.” ((🤓))
"Hmph, I don't need sass from a minion. Know your place, and accept the praise of Voreverl Leocot gratefully."
“Voreverl… it just ticks me off! Don’t like the name, sorry. Nothing against you. But jeez. Something about that.”

"Nothing... against me? Oh, that's real interesting... I thought for sure you would have some kind of reason for insulting my very existence. Or are you just too stupid to realize what kind of enemy you can make with talk like that. Huh? What is it!?" She gets all up in his face.
“You’re somewhat unpleasant, I guess. But not enough to be unbearable. I wonder. Were you that surprised by my attire because you’ve never held an actual job before?” He asks this calmly.

"I... I'm the *only* person to hold an actual job! I rule the world! I destroy civilizations! Gweheheh, whatever you did, it has nothing on me! You're the fake! Just, just... dressing how you're supposed to... doing what you're told... it's disgusting!"

“Oh, which ones? The civilization of your own credit score?” He chuckles adultly. “Look, I’d honestly have guessed you were from the fantasy world, not earth. This won’t do you any favors in the latter.”

"That attitude is why your life will amount to nothing. Oh, Joe, you need to wear a suit and tie. Oh, Joe, you need to work at The Antarctica Project. Oh, Joe, you need to stand in this void for 25 years. You're just... just a nobody! No one will remember you! But they'll remember me. I don't need a credit score. I don't need to work at a zoo. I'll reinvent society, just wait."
“It definitely hasn’t been 25 years.” He mutters.

"...Yeah, you look pretty human. I don't know how it works for those Arctican creatures, but even a villain as resilient as me couldn't survive in this place that long. Is there even any cereal, or, like, water here?"
“Hm. No, I haven’t seen any. Curious. I wonder if that will become a problem.”
"I'll see if I can bring some to you next time. Assuming I actually get out of here. It's never taken this long before. Gweheheh, might have to break my way out at this rate."
“I would be interested to see such a thing, were it possible.”
((Session fcuking end))
“I don’t think it’s possible, though.” He muses.

Voreverl crosses her arms, annoyed "Clearly you still don't understand who you're dealing with here. This place is no different from prison, and if modern security can't hold Voreverl Leocot, then this dinky little Antarctica Project doesn't stand a chance."
“There are no bars or restraints.”

"Just what I'd expect to hear from an unimaginative, boring office worker. Your life is the constraint! You just... accept the slop fed to you. I'm different. I broke out of Jane's prison, and I'll break out of Bern's too, so just watch me break out of this one. I'll make the criminal justice system into nothing more than my own personal revolving door!"

“Jane…” He mutters the name back to himself, and keeps typing up a storm on the inexplicable void terminal. “I just don’t think those skills are transferable, regardless of the possibility of escape.”

"I guess not. That's why I don't throw all my eggs at one house. I'm not some one-off gimmick villain, I'm the real deal. Adaptability, that's how you stay societally relevant. I won't be left behind just because the stage for my tyranny has changed."
“Oh. Something new… hm.” A video feed is displayed.
Voreverl turns her attention to the monitor.
It looks like the facility where Voreverl confronted John Leiblich. The feed buffers and slowly rises in quality.

"...What? Is this... Gweheheh, maybe this rest stop won't be a total waste of my valuable and important time. I don't suppose there's a remote detonation feature anywhere on this program? Maybe something to vent in toxic gas?"

It shows the last minute or so of the confrontation as Voreverl remembers it.

“Where… I know this guy. I’m certain I do.” The man in the void mumbles.

It reaches the end of Voreverl’s involvement, as she leaves in the direction of Eric Zeety.

"I can't say you keep particularly good company. That pathetic fool is John Leiblich, a two-bit pesky fly who fancies himself a full fledged villain. This footage is from when I completely beat him in a battle of wits and guile, leaving his plans and mental state in ruins, so they can better match his marriage."
“John Leiblich…. John Leiblich. ……John Leiblich. No, that can’t be right.”
"...Why not? That's his name. If anyone knows the name of John Leiblich, trust me, I'm the person. I've spent my life loathing that name of his."

“No! This is not John Leiblich!” He holds his head.

The two women that Voreverl may or may not know as Joliene Swansong and Zita Praxis continue their standoff with Leiblich.

"That's a great objection you got there. Come back to me when you have a theory of your own. Or don't, I don't really care. I know I'm right, after all. Although, seeing you squirm in confusion would be a decent way to pass the time."

The two women, both armed, corner John Leiblich. He stammers through negotiations and frees the two people he had imprisoned after failing to call his unconscious guards.

“How can you even say that for certain?! You probably just made some mistake!” Computer man cares way too much about this issue.
Voreverl starts to tune him out and stares at the monitor with a stupid smirk "Gweheheheh... Let him off too easy, honestly... Huh? Oh, you still on about this?"

The feed fast forwards through Joliene literally just reading a book and nothing else happening for a substantial amount of time.

“Why can’t I remember? I shouldn’t even need to be struggling to do that, how could I forget!”

"You forgot because it isn't important. I told you, this guy's a chump, a complete and utter waste of time. It's honestly a shame I haven't forgotten who he is. In fact, I'll probably do that once I completely crush him underneath my heel."

Joliene mentions something about dungeons and dragons that upsets the man more.

As a shouting match over some nonsense about a guy named Detlef ensues on the feed, computer man continues to be agitated. “No, you’re wrong! He’s important!”

Voreverl gives the computer man a look of disgust "Said no one with a single brain cell ever. He's a footnote in my backstory. He probably won't even be explicitly named in chapters on my rise in history textbooks. You have picked the most pathetic possible molehill to die on."

Computer man grunts in annoyance at her, but otherwise ignores Voreverl. He stares at the display, straining to understand… something.

On the screen, John has been pummeled twice by the furious queen.

"Fuck! Come on, I'm-- he's fine! I don't have direct control over all these mechanisms, but they're tested and safe! I don't like the guy, but that project head understands how to... run this sorta thing." John Leiblich pants desperately.

Joliene exasperatedly steps between the two.
"Zita, you're—Look, I understand that you're frustrated, but this is a futile effort." She stabs John in the neck without even turning to face him. "I'm going to have to stop this here. You're just going to give yourself a migraine. I have it in good faith that he has no useful info for us. We must move on." Joliene removes the blade. John Leiblich collapses and bleeds out on the ground.

“WHAT?” Computer man screams reactively. “WHAT THE FUCK IS THAT?”

"..." The blood drains from Voreverl's face, and she takes a step back "That... that... that's great... it... I wanted... gweh... I... urgh..." Voreverl's stomach begins to churn, and with a completely blank mind, she is unable to stop herself from falling to her knees and puking.
The vomit pools and dissipates in the nothing. ((What a description.))
The other man seems to pass out.

"What... what the fuck is wrong with him... dying before I killed him... I..." Tears well up in her eyes "I WASN'T DONE WITH HIM YET! He... He... THIS ISN'T HOW MY BACKSTORY GOES!!!" Voreverl gathers all of her strength to lift herself up and thrust herself forward towards the computer, attempting to punch through the monitor without even thinking.
((Roll strength.))
It shatters.
"...No! Fuck! What happens next!? Where did they go!? Uh, uh..." She turns to the computer man, and kicks him in the side "Wake up! Fix this!"

The computer man doesn’t wake up. 

But someone else shows up. It’s difficult to see… the person appears almost pure black against a background which is also that. But there’s a clear humanoid presence.
”He can’t fix this. Nothing really broke, anyway. Not physically.”

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: "Fuck... Fuck! I should have been there! I should have... I wasn't done yet! I wasn't done! He... I still had plans! I still had plans! Dying to another low-rate... That asshole! Does he think dying can make up for everything! He deserves so much worse... I could have done worse! I should have!"

I maneuver towards shards of what once was a video feed, suspended in the air. I grab hold of one.
“Would that have helped? Would you have been satisfied?”

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: "Y-yeah! Obviously! I... I needed my revenge! I didn't get it from him yet... I just... I just needed more time! He... He ruined my life! How can I be fine with his ending like that!? How!? How is this happening!?"

“Because of the greatest waste of time ever conceived. The Antarctica Project. He died for none of his real sins or actions, but for interfering with something so trivial. And through the incompetence of two women in particular, on a smaller scale.”

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: "That's... that's right..." She balls up her fists "This project... This... This fucking circus show! That's my enemy! That's why I was put in that body! That's why I went through all of this... Why Eric... Ugh!" She stomps in anger "How do I kill it? Pulverize it! Destroy this fucking tumor on my perfect scheme!?"
”I cannot provide you everything. After all, you shouldnt even have a real reason to trust me. But I can provide one guarantee, and one spot of hope.”

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: "You..." Voreverl finally begins centering some of her attention on the presence speaking to her "Who... Gweheh... It doesn't matter... Nobody important, I'm sure..."

”Not particularly, no. I have no real name. Perhaps you can call me Autumn. Though you should have no need to refer to me. The spot of hope is this: The consciousness of that man should not be fully lost. In the same way Strider over here can exist, it may be possible for me to retrieve his essence.” I gesture to the sunglasses man, since Voreverl probably wouldn’t get who I’m referring to.

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: "That... Gweh... Gwehahahahah! So... the afterlife is real now!? What, am I going to hell? Super hell? Sure, why not! Get him back in here! He isn't done suffering yet! I'm not... I can't be done yet!"

”It is sort of like hell. …The more confident guarantee is chances for retribution against most other relevant figures. You will meet TGP and PH. You will overcome impossibility to meet Bernard Zie. You’ll become an incredible despot. …And you’ll meet the two who killed your father. Whatever conflicted feelings you have on them is your business. But me personally, I’m rooting against them.”

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: I crush the shard of an image within my hands, hoping that looks cool.

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: I look up. “What the fuck is he doing? Oh, god dammit.”

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content: "...Don't tell me what I'm going to do. The universe is against me! Society too! If I get my revenge on this project... On whoever else is in my way... It will be because of my own effort! I'm going to do it because I want to, not because you told me to! Don't tell me shit I already know! Of course I'll be incredible, I'm Voreverl Leocot!"

”Oh, absolutely. I don’t actually ‘do’ anything.”

I leave.

roles.name: if women are oppressed then why

messages.content:
Voreverl can barely even parse being left alone before she ceases to be in this space.

((End session. End 14.5.))
